  "passages": [
    {
      "id": "fog-collectors",
      "title": "Fog collectors",
      "content": [
        { "kind": "paragraph", "runs": [{ "kind": "text", "value": "Fog collectors use vertical mesh to intercept tiny airborne water droplets. In a twelve-week project, researchers compared a fine mesh with a coarser mesh at two coastal sites. On an exposed ridge, the fine mesh captured more water per square metre before maintenance was considered. At the lower site, however, salt and dust blocked the fine mesh more quickly. Because it required frequent cleaning, the fine mesh delivered less usable water there than the coarse mesh." }] },
        { "kind": "paragraph", "runs": [{ "kind": "text", "value": "Both designs fed covered storage tanks. The researchers measured water entering the tanks but did not measure losses during later distribution to homes. The trial ran in spring and neither design was tested in winter. The team concluded that mesh choice should take account of local wind, airborne particles and the staff time available for maintenance, rather than relying only on a headline capture rate." }] }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "museum-digitisation",
      "title": "A museum digitisation project",
      "content": [
        { "kind": "paragraph", "runs": [{ "kind": "text", "value": "A regional museum holds about 20,000 objects. Over two years it created online records for 800 objects, selecting items that were fragile, frequently requested or difficult to display. Online views rose steadily while physical visits remained close to their previous level. In a voluntary website survey, 60 per cent of respondents said that they lived outside the region." }] },
        { "kind": "paragraph", "runs": [{ "kind": "text", "value": "Scanning was only one part of the work. Each record also required a description, rights checks and links to related material. Trained volunteers drafted some descriptions, but a curator checked every record before publication. A donor funded the first two years. The museum has not yet announced whether the same level of funding will continue. Staff regard the project as a useful way to widen access, but they do not claim that an online record can replace examining every object in person." }] }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "street-trees",
      "title": "Street trees and summer temperature",
      "content": [
        { "kind": "paragraph", "runs": [{ "kind": "text", "value": "Researchers monitored twenty city streets for three summers. Ten streets received new trees and ten did not. By the third summer, sensors on the planted streets recorded an average midday temperature 1.2°C lower than sensors on the comparison streets. Average night-time temperatures did not differ. Eighty-eight per cent of the new trees survived to the end of the study." }] },
        { "kind": "paragraph", "runs": [{ "kind": "text", "value": "The streets were matched for width and traffic, but they were not assigned randomly: trees could be planted only where underground utilities left enough space. The researchers therefore warned that unmeasured differences might remain. Trees were irrigated during the first two summers; rainfall was typical in the third. The study did not include a severe drought, and the average cooling figure does not mean that every planted street was cooler on every day." }] }
      ]
    }
  ],
